sh for waste reduction tempered the environmental impacts of Model T mass production; how Elvis Presley's widely shared postwar desire for Cadillacs made matters worse; how the 1970s energy crisis hurt small cars; and why baby boomers ignored worries about global warming. McCarthy shows that problems were recognized early. The difficulty was addressing them, a matter less of doing scientific research and educating the public than implementing solutions through America's market economy and democratic government. Consumer and producer interests have rarely aligned in helpful ways, and automakers and consumers have made powerful opponents of regulation. The result has been a mixed record of environmental reform with troubling prospects for the future.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAutomobile industry and tradexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aAutomobile industry and tradezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAutomobilesxEnvironmental aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aAutomobilesxEnvironmental aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aConsumer behaviorxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aConsumer behaviorzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aTechnology & Engineering / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300150025423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300150025.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles